'''Ōkume no Mikoto''' (大久米命) is a legendary figure from ancient {{ill|Japan|ja|日本}}, recorded in texts such as the {{ill|Kojiki|ja|古事記}} and {{ill|Nihon Shoki|ja|日本書紀}}. He is revered as the ancestor of the {{ill|Kumebe|ja|久米直}} clan, a prominent ancient warrior lineage. The *Nihon Shoki* sometimes refers to him as "Ōkume" (大来目).

== Genealogy ==
According to the *Kojiki*, Ōkume no Mikoto joined the {{ill|Eastern Expedition|ja|神武東征}} of {{ill|Emperor Jimmu|ja|神武天皇}}, alongside {{ill|Michinoomi no Mikoto|ja|道臣命}} (ancestor of the {{ill|Ōtomo clan|ja|大伴氏}}). Together, they defeated local chieftains such as {{ill|Eukashi|ja|兄猾}}, the {{ill|Tsuchigumo|ja|土蜘蛛}} lord {{ill|Yasotakeru|ja|八十梟帥}}, and other opponents in the {{ill|Yamato Province|ja|大和国}}.<ref name="jimmu">*Kojiki*, middle volume, Emperor Jimmu section.</ref> His actions are celebrated in the *Nihon Shoki*, which notes the singing of {{ill|Kumeuta|ja|久米歌}}, martial songs to inspire warriors during battle.<ref>*Nihon Shoki*, Emperor Jimmu pre-enthronement, year戊午, 10th month, 2nd day.</ref>

The *Kojiki* identifies Ōkume no Mikoto’s ancestor as {{ill|Amatsukume no Mikoto|ja|天津久米命}},<ref>*Kojiki*, upper volume, Tenson Ninigi section.</ref> while the *Nihon Shoki* refers to him as "Ame Kushitsu Ōkume" (天槵津大来目). Both sources agree on their role as protectors of the {{ill|Heavenly Grandchild|ja|天孫}}, indicating a long-standing military tradition.

== Legacy ==
In the *Kojiki*, Ōkume no Mikoto is depicted as an equal partner to Michinoomi no Mikoto in leading Emperor Jimmu's forces. However, in the *Nihon Shoki*, Ōkume is portrayed as subordinate, suggesting that the Kumebe clan's influence declined over time, with leadership passing to the Ōtomo clan.

The *Kojiki* also records Ōkume’s role in arranging Emperor Jimmu’s marriage to {{ill|Isukeyorihime|ja|伊須気余理比売}}. During the courtship, Ōkume performed a {{ill|Sedōka|ja|旋頭歌}} that refers to "tattooed eyes," implying he may have worn traditional warrior tattoos.<ref name="jimmu" />

