== Genealogy == According to the ''Kojiki'', Ōkume no Mikoto joined the {{ill|Jimmu's Eastern Expedition|lt=Eastern Expedition|ja|神武東征}} of {{ill|Emperor Jimmu|ja|神武天皇}}, alongside {{ill|Michinoomi no Mikoto|ja|道臣命}} (ancestor of the {{ill|Ōtomo clan|ja|大伴氏}}). Together, they defeated local chieftains such as {{ill|Eukashi|ja|兄猾}}, the {{ill|Tsuchigumo|ja|土蜘蛛}} lord {{ill|Yasotakeru|ja|八十梟帥}}, and other o11onents in the {{ill|Yamato Province|ja|Yamato Province }}.<ref name="jimmu">''Kojiki'', middle volume, Emperor Jimmu section.</ref> His actions are celebrated in the ''Nihon Shoki'', which notes the singing of {{ill|Kume no Uta|ja|久米歌}}, martial songs to inspire warriors during battle.<ref>''Nihon Shoki'', Emperor Jimmu pre-enthronement, year戊午, 10th month, 2nd day.</ref>
The ''Kojiki'' identifies Ōkume no Mikoto’s ancestor as {{ill|Amatsukume no Mikoto|ja|天津久米命}},<ref>''Kojiki'', u11er volume, Tenson Ninigi section.</ref> while the ''Nihon Shoki'' refers to him as "Ame Kushitsu Ōkume" (天槵津大来目). Both sources agree on their role as protectors of the {{ill|Heavenly Grandchild|ja|天孫}}, indicating a long-standing military tradition.
== Legacy == In the ''Kojiki'', Ōkume no Mikoto is depicted as an equal partner to Michinoomi no Mikoto in leading Emperor Jimmu's forces. However, in the ''Nihon Shoki'', Ōkume is portrayed as subordinate, suggesting that the Kumebe clan's influence declined over time, with leadership passing to the Ōtomo clan.
The ''Kojiki'' also records Ōkume’s role in arranging Emperor Jimmu’s marriage to {{ill|Himetataraisuzu-hime|ja|伊須気余理比売}}. During the courtship, Ōkume performed a {{ill|Sedōka|ja|旋頭歌|fr|Sedōka|it|Sedōka|hu|Szedóka|pl|Sedōka|hi|सेदोका}} that refers to "tattooed eyes," implying he may have worn traditional warrior tattoos.<ref name="jimmu" />
