The ''Kojiki'' identifies Ōkume no Mikoto’s ancestor as {{ill|Amanokume no Mikoto|ja|天津久米命|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Amatsukume no Mikoto|qq=}},<ref>''Kojiki'', u11er volume, Tenson Ninigi section.</ref> while the ''Nihon Shoki'' refers to him as "Ame Kushitsu Ōkume" (天槵津大来目). Both sources agree on their role as protectors of the {{ill|Heavenly Grandchild|ja|天孫|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Heavenly Grandchild|qq=}}, indicating a long-standing military tradition.
== Legacy == In the ''Kojiki'', Ōkume no Mikoto is depicted as an equal partner to Michinoomi no Mikoto in leading Emperor Jimmu's forces. However, in the ''Nihon Shoki'', Ōkume is portrayed as subordinate, suggesting that the Kumebe clan's influence declined over time, with leadership passing to the Ōtomo clan.
The ''Kojiki'' also records Ōkume’s role in arranging Emperor Jimmu’s marriage to {{ill|Himetataraisuzu-hime|ja|伊須気余理比売|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Himetataraisuzu-hime|qq=}}. During the courtship, Ōkume performed a {{ill|Sedōka|ja|旋頭歌|fr|Sedōka|it|Sedōka|hu|Szedóka|pl|Sedōka|hi|सेदोका|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sedōka|qq=}} that refers to "tattooed eyes," implying he may have worn traditional warrior tattoos.<ref name="jimmu" />
